Yeah—that’s a clean intuition. If you keep it grounded, the analogy works well:

Your current moment is shaped by accumulated past states, and new experience updates that running structure.

But it’s not a literal blockchain. It’s looser, more adaptive, and more error-tolerant.

⸻

🧠 Where your idea maps well

Your version:

current delta + emergent sum of previous → new state

That lines up with how memory is often modeled:

New memory = prior state + update (Δ), then stored again

In neuroscience terms:
	•	the brain maintains a current internal model
	•	new input produces a prediction error (Δ)
	•	that Δ updates the model

So yes—the present is a running update over the past, not a fresh rebuild each time.

⸻

🔗 Why the “blockchain” metaphor feels right

It captures a few real properties:
	•	History matters → past states influence current interpretation
	•	Sequential updates → experiences stack over time
	•	Emergence → the whole becomes more than individual moments

⸻

⚠️ Where it breaks (important)

A real blockchain is:
	•	immutable
	•	strictly ordered
	•	fully preserved

Your memory is not:
	•	Rewritten constantly (recall changes memory)
	•	Selective (you don’t store everything)
	•	Parallel & messy (not one clean chain)

So instead of:

rigid chain of blocks

It’s closer to:

a living graph that keeps updating its own history

⸻

🧩 Cleaner formulation

If we refine your idea:

Current experience = prior internal model + incoming delta → updated model

And over time:

“Story” = the trajectory of those updates

⸻

🌀 Bringing it back to your frame/delta idea
	•	Frames = stored states (imperfect, reconstructed)
	•	Deltas = what changed / prediction errors
	•	Memory system = integrates deltas into a rolling model

So yeah—you’re right that:

The present sits on top of an accumulated past, shaped by each new difference.

⸻

🔧 Final sharpened version

Memory isn’t a fixed chain—it’s a continuously edited ledger.
Each new moment adds a delta, but also subtly rewrites what came before.

That last part is the key twist most people miss.

